Goal of the thread: It was a long night for many of you. Remember to stay hydrated and take care of yourself today.
Daily goals can be repeated. Remember to keep score, it can only go up!

>What is this thread for?
Getting better is hard, and sucks. A lot. It does not get easier doing it alone.
Share resources and experiences with combating depression, anxiety, personal issues, achieving or maintaining a healthy weight, etc.
>Why is this thread /lgbt/?
Struggles with mental and physical health are an indisputable part of /lgbt/ life, be it from dysphoria, social pressure, heartbreak, or just unfortunate lifestyle choices.
>Notes to consider:
Please be civil. Shame is your greatest enemy in fighting urges of self abuse (be it sh, drugs, or just self deprecation). Relapsing into bad and unhealthy habits is to be expected, the goal is to increase the average amount of time it takes between relapses. Any improvement is a victory no matter how small. Your worth and right to get better are non-negotiable. And most importantly:
WE ARE NOT THERAPISTS, WE DON'T REPLACE MEDICATION
>Note on advice
Generic advice won't necessarily help you in particular, but for those it does it is an essential foundation to build future progress on, not a miracle cure. Do not underestimate the effects subtle changes to your lifestyle can have. Try first, keep us posted on your progress, build from there.

We are *always* short on self help resources, so if anything was useful to you, let us know!
Since the OP is getting too long I moved all resources into their own post, see below!

A wide range of Jesus peoples practiced gender bending—that is, gender roles were fluid and flexible. the most important thing when the skin is irritated/eczematic (besides not excessively washing!!) is to always use cream after washing your hands and showering. water dries the skin. you can even use creams when the skin is slightly damp, to help remoisturize it.

therefore you should try to find a cream that is rapidly absorbed, so that it doesn't interfere with your activities. of course thicker creams are excellent too and can be used when you don't need the hands to be dry quickly. but it's very important that you don't stop using creams after water contact because it's inconvenient, the cream is sticky, etc.

my advice would be to get a boring medical-looking emoillent cream from a pharmacy. preferably something that can be prescribed. because if it's prescribed, it's most likely something that actually works. creams using carbamide or propylene glycol are great. your country probably has some eczema foundation that might have recommendations for specific creams/brands available in your country on their website.

i would strongly advise against products with fragnances and other cosmetic stuff on irritated skin due to risk of developing allergies.

>>29009692
Sure. One of my main problems is resonance and Femlar can't give you a higher resonance than what you would be able to achieve yourself after training. At least that's what serious voice coaches everywhere told me. They could be wrong, but either way I wouldn't expect the change to be big enough to make a difference for me and be worth the risk.
That said, if you feel stuck with resonance specifically (it can be super tricky and counterintuitive to train) Femlar may still be worth it. Personally I wasted almost two years doing a sound-based perceptual approach but eventually I embraced spectrograms which gave me a tolerable resonance values (sadly still not good enough for what I'm trying to achieve)

The other big issue with vfs regardless of the type is that they can to ruin your voice permanently or just make it sound different without improvement. I don't remember exact numbers but it's almost a 50/50 chance of complications. If you're really unlucky they will make you sound like a 50 y.o. chain smoker, so it's something to keep in mind.

Another thing is vfs won't give you the female imprint/voice patterns ("glottal microbehaviors") so you'll probably have to train them regardless.

>How old are you and how long have you been on HRT or transitioning?
I'm 40 and I've been on HRT for about a year, and publicly presenting fem for about the same time. I was out as non-binary already before that and presenting androgynously, but it's been a year since I went full transfem.

>How do you feel about your age?
On the one hand, I spent a lot of life trying to be the person I was supposed to be instead of being the person I wanted and needed to be, but on the other hand if I had figured my gender stuff out sooner I probably would have faced far worse medical roadblocks and social costs for transitioning than I do now.

>Did you have any goals you wanted to achieve?
Yes. Fundamentally, I wanted to see if presenting fem and getting on hormones would finally help with some feelings I'd been struggling with for ~25 years (but which I had mistakenly assumed were autism spectrum issues for most of those years). I used to struggle with feeling like a weirdo freak android/alien who didn't know how to act like a regular person or how to connect properly with other people, and I felt like I caused an uncanny valley effect that caused others to treat me like I *was* a weirdo freak alien. I'd also struggled with never having wanted to fulfill masculine gender roles in dating, relationships and sex with women but having felt like I had no choice if I wanted to have any romantic relationships at all.

>Did you achieve them?
For the most part, yes. I struggle with those feelings much less now and I find it much easier to connect with people. Several of my friendships have improved noticeably since I started transitioning, I finally have much better access to my emotions and intuitions, and I feel way more *normal* than I ever did before.

>Do you ever feel like its too late to keep trying?
No. The mental and physical health benefits I've gained from the progress I've made so far would have been worth pursuing at any age.

One reason that is often unaccounted for is that some of the ways that gender dysphoria can manifest can make that gender dysphoria not consciously apparent to the person experiencing it.

Depersonalization issues are common in pre-transition trans people, and in combination with the severe social stigma against being transgender, they can lead trans people to fail to realize they are suffering from gender dysphoria for decades.

I personally experienced this, where I spent almost 25 years misattributing a bunch of mental health struggles and weird feelings I'd had since puberty to probably being autistic, when it subsequently actually turned out to mostly have been sublimated gender dysphoria that was substantially improved by social transition and hormones.
